        "messageId": "75f07cbf-008f-4a48-a4d0-0a9a0e994611",
        "content": "110/110 passing. Here's what was found and fixed:\n\n---\n\n**Two real bugs in the explicit-review diversity path:**\n\n### Bug 1 — `orderCandidates` (wrong scope of deprioritisation)\n\n`isSameModelFamily` compares *sub-families* (`claude-sonnet` vs `claude-opus` vs `gpt-5` etc.). It returns `false` for `claude-opus-4.5` vs `claude-sonnet-4.6` — different sub-families. So after ordering, `claude-opus-4.5` received a score of 0, the same as GPT models, and appeared *before* later GPT candidates (`gpt-5.1-codex-max`, `gpt-5.2`, etc.) in the sorted list. A review could be fulfilled by a Claude model even when GPT was available.\n\n**Fix:** replaced `isSameModelFamily` with `getModelFamily` (broad family: `claude` vs `gpt`) so *all* Claude models are pushed behind *all* GPT models when the last implementation also used Claude, regardless of sub-family.\n\n### Bug 2 — `buildAdditionalContext` (missing fallback note)\n\nSame root cause. `isSameModelFamily(\"claude-opus-4.5\", \"claude-sonnet-4.6\")` returns `false`, so the fallback note — *\"A distinct review model was not available, so the router fell back…\"* — was silently dropped when review landed on `claude-opus` after `claude-sonnet` impl. The agent believed diversity was achieved.\n\n**Fix:** replaced `isSameModelFamily` with `getModelFamily` equality check so the note fires whenever review and impl share the same broad provider family.\n\n**5 new regression tests** cover both directions (Claude-after-Claude, GPT-after-GPT, and the successful cross-family cases).",
